r><tr><td><p>2016-17<sup>4</sup></p></td><td><p>ESA</p></td><td><p><em>638</em></p></td><td><p><em>272</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>PIP</p></td><td><p><em>846</em></p></td><td><p><em>410</em></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><ol><li><em> SSCS data are attributed to the hearing venue nearest to the appellant’s home address. The data above represent appellants with home addresses in the Stroud district who had appeals heard at the Tribunal’s Gloucester, Swindon and previously Cheltenham venues. Appeals were last listed to the Cheltenham venue in May 2017.</em></li></ol><p> </p><ol start="2"><li><em> Includes ESA and ESA (Reassessments).</em></li></ol><p> </p><p><em><sup>3. </sup></em><em>PIP replaced Disability Living Allowance (DLA) for people aged 16 to 64 and rolled out from 8 April 2013. It was trialled in areas of the North of England and gradually rolled out across other regions. As such there were no appeals cleared in the Stroud district in 2013-2014.</em></p><p> </p><ol start="4"><li><em> By financial year - from 1 April to 31 March. </em></li></ol><p> </p><ol start="5"><li><em>Denotes appeal types where fewer than five cases were involved and therefore data are statistically unreliable.</em></li></ol><p> </p><p><em>Although care is taken when processing and analysing the data, the details are subject to inaccuracies inherent in any large-scale case management system and are the best data available. The data are a subset of official statistics extracted from the case management system on a different date.</em></p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-11T15:46:07.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747608/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747608/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747608/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-03","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) employment and support allowance and (b) personal independence payment appeals there have been in the Stroud District in each year since 2010; and how many such appeals were successful.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","2628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747609","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-11","<p>The £3 billion Home Building Fund provides long and short term loan finance to build the homes this country needs. To date the fund has allocated £1.181 billion (40 per cent) to successful applicants.</p><p>Of the £1 billion short term fund £0.445 billion (44 per cent) has been allocated to successful applicants. The proportion of schemes which will be delivered by small and medium sized builders is 70 per cent. Of which, nearly 90 per cent of these sites have fewer than 100 homes.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-11T16:23:48.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747609/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747609/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747609/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-03","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of successful applications to the Home Building Fund have been submitted by builders delivering less than 100 units per year since the introduction of that fund.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","2558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747611","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-14","<p>In October 2016, the Government launched the £3 billion Home Building Fund, a fund which will provide loans for SME builders, custom builders and offsite construction, and which will unlock large sites throughout England. The £3 billion Home Building Fund is broken down into two funds:</p><p>The £1 billion short term fund (STF) is available to small builders, custom builders and innovators and the £2 billion long term fund (LTF) is to deliver infrastructure and site preparation for large sites, including brown field.</p><p>The below table presents, the proportion of the Home Building Fund (in terms of projects supported) in each region, as recorded by the Homes and Communities Agency, and broken down into long term funding and short term funding. Percentages may not total 100 per cent, as they are rounded to the nearest per cent.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>HCA Region</p></td><td><p>LTF</p></td><td><p>STF</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East &amp; South East</p></td><td><p>31%</p></td><td><p>6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>25%</p></td><td><p>3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Midlands</p></td><td><p>19%</p></td><td><p>18%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East, Yorkshire &amp; Humber</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>41%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td><td><p>14%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South &amp; South West</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>National</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td><td><p>5%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>National projects are projects where sites are being delivered over multiple areas. This category also includes the £50 million which has been committed to the Housing Growth Partnership.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-14T12:01:35.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747611/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747611/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-03","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of the Home Building Fund has been allocated to property developers in each region since October 2016.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","2557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747612","Department for Education","false","2017-07-06","<p>Ofsted is the non-ministerial government department responsible for the inspection of schools and childcare providers and publishes a regular series of statistics relating to inspection on its website, which can be viewed from this link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/ofsted/about/statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/ofsted/about/statistics</a></p><p>We have informed Ofsted of this question and Her Majesty's Chief Inspector will be writing to the hon. Member in response. A copy of that letter will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-06T08:43:59.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747612/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747612/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-03","Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of the (a) maintained schools, (b) non-maintained schools, (c) independent schools, (d) providers on the Early Years Register and (e) providers registered with an early years childminder agency which provide early years foundation stage have been assessed as (i) outstanding, (ii) good, (iii) satisfactory and (iv) inadequate.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","2607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747613","Department for Education","false","2017-07-06","<p>Ofsted is the non-ministerial government department responsible for the regulation of early education and childcare providers and publishes a regular series of statistics relating to inspection of this provision on its website, which can be viewed from this link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/ofsted/about/statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/ofsted/about/statistics</a></p><p>We have informed Ofsted of this question and Her Majesty's Chief Inspector will be writing to the hon. Member in response. A copy of that letter will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-06T08:49:13.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747613/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747613/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-03","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of early years foundation stage providers have been assessed as (a) outstanding, (b) good, (c) satisfactory and (d) inadequate in (i) each region in England and (ii) England.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","2533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747614","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-10","<p>We are working with the sector to make it quicker and easier to switch supplier and are working with Ofgem to move to even faster and more reliable switching.</p><p>Ofgem are working on developing better ways to engage consumers and on 3 July announced trials to help customers on expensive standard tariffs find and switch to cheaper energy deals.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-10T15:34:21.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747614/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747614/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747614/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747614/answer/previousversion/2446","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03","Energy: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps are being taken to encourage householders to seek the cheapest energy deals available to them to help them to cut energy bills.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","2376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747615","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-10","<p>Customers in fuel poverty use a range of methods to pay their energy bills. Latest BEIS Fuel Poverty data published on 29 June 2017 shows that in 2015, of the 2,885,000 households who paid for their gas supply by prepayment meter, 613,000 were fuel poor. Of the 3,550,000 million households who paid for their electricity supply by prepayment meter, 776,000 were fuel poor.</p><p>From 1 April this year, as a result of action by Competition Markets Authority, a cap on the amount energy suppliers can charge prepayment customers was introduced. The cap covers 4.5 million households saving many dual fuel customers £80 a year.</p><p>On 3 July Ofgem announced proposals to cap warrant charges to install prepayment meters and ban these charges altogether for the most vulnerable.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-10T15:34:05.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747615/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747615/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747615/answer/previousversion/2443","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03","Energy: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps are being taken to protect poorer households from fuel poverty caused by the high prices of pre-payment energy meters.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","2377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747616","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-06","<p><strong>Details of the costs associated with the Article 50 case will be published in due course.</strong></p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-06T16:04:23.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747616/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747616/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-03","Brexit: Judgements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, when he plans to disclose the cost of the Supreme Court case R (on the application of Miller and another) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","2403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747617","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>We have announced the first six challenges of the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund (ISCF) that will bring together the world leading research from across the UK with business to meet major industrial and societal challenges. The ISCF is a UK wide fund so its competitions for funding, and the programmes it will deliver, will be open to businesses and researchers across the UK.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-07-11T09:51:22.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747617/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747617/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03","Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how his Department will ensure that the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund complements existing initiatives in Scotland to deliver an holistic approach to innovation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","2587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747618","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer I gave him to Question UIN 411 on 29th June 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-07-11T14:53:23.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747618/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747618/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03","Industry: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to ensure closer collaboration between the Government and the Scottish Government in relation to the Government's Industrial Strategy.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","2586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747619","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-11","<p>We have pursued a wide-ranging programme of engagement since the Department was created in order to build a national consensus around our negotiating position.</p><p>We are speaking to a significant number of organisations and individuals, including businesses in Scotland, to establish their priorities and understand their concerns.</p><p><strong><br></strong>Details of Ministerial and senior official meetings will be published in the Department’s Quarterly Transparency Returns, which will be made publicly available on GOV.UK.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-11T14:19:56.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747619/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747619/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-03","Business: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how his Department is providing opportunities for Scottish businesses to feed into the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","2584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747620","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>The objective of Government’s Industrial Strategy is to increase productivity and drive growth across the United Kingdom. We have provided a framework to build on the strengths of different places and address the factors that hold others back. This will include investing in key infrastructure projects, increasing skill levels, and backing local innovation strengths.</p><p>The Industrial Strategy will build on the £12 billion Local Growth Fund (2015-16 to 2020-21) for local areas; 8 Devolution Deals; and 48 Enterprise Zones that will unlock £2.7 billion of private sector investment. We have also agreed ambitious city deals in Scotland and Wales and we will work towards further such deals across the Devolved Administrations.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-11T15:16:49.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747620/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747620/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03","Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how the Government is addressing the regional productivity gap in each region and constituent part of the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","2585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747621","Department of Health","false","2017-07-06","<p>The data on BRCA1/2 testing rates is now available for 2014/15 and 2015/16 for England and Scotland. The published data can be downloaded from the UK Genetic Testing Network website at:</p><p><a href="https://ukgtn.nhs.uk/resources/ukgtn-reports/ukgtn-molecular-genetic-test-activity-rates-in-the-united-kingdom/" target="_blank">https://ukgtn.nhs.uk/resources/ukgtn-reports/ukgtn-molecular-genetic-test-activity-rates-in-the-united-kingdom/</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-06T09:52:32.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747621/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747621/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-03","Genetics: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to publish the data from the BRC1/2 tests carried out by the UK Genetic Testing Network.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","2423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747622","Department of Health","false","2017-07-06","<p>Public Health England (PHE) has published one full evaluation report on the pilot campaign and one interim report on the regional campaign for the Be Clear on Cancer ovarian cancer campaign.</p><p> </p><p>The full evaluation of the local ovarian cancer pilot campaign which ran from 14 January – 17 March 2013 it can be accessed here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ovarian-cancer-awareness-campaign-local-pilots-evaluation-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ovarian-cancer-awareness-campaign-local-pilots-evaluation-report</a></p><p> </p><p>The interim evaluation report on the regional ovarian cancer awareness campaign, which ran from 10 February- 16 March 2014 in the North West of England it can be accessed here:</p><p><a href="http://www.ncin.org.uk/cancer_type_and_topic_specific_work/topic_specific_work/be_clear_on_cancer/" target="_blank">http://www.ncin.org.uk/cancer_type_and_topic_specific_work/topic_specific_work/be_clear_on_cancer/</a></p><p> </p><p>PHE is planning to produce a full and final evaluation report for the Be Clear on Cancer ovarian cancer awareness regional campaign by April 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s Policy Research Unit on Cancer Awareness Screening and Early Diagnosis has undertaken a qualitative research study in which members of the public were given access to available leaflets on ovarian cancer awareness and then participated in six focus groups and interviews on their acceptability and how they would be received and understood if included within the clear screening results letter from the breast or cervical screening programme.</p><p> </p><p>This study is now complete and has been presented at the recent Cancer Research UK Early Diagnosis conference. The work is currently being written up for submission to a peer-reviewed medical journal. The Health Research Authority approval for a further qualitative research study with professionals has now been granted, and the work is in progress.</p><p> </p><p>A second project is a synthesis of published incidence, mortality, stage distribution and stage-specific survival rates for ovarian cancer by age. The aim of this project was to identify which age group would be most likely to benefit from such an intervention, in terms of risk of ovarian cancer, and room for improvement in stage at diagnosis. This study is now also complete, fully written up, and has been submitted to a journal for publication. The journal’s response is awaited.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-07-06T14:52:45.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747622/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747622/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-03","Ovarian Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to publish the two research studies into ovarian cancer awareness which the previous Government indicated it planned to publish in the summer of 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","2424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747623","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-11","<p>The tender process is managed by the St Helena Government. On 9 June, the St Helena Government announced that SA Airlink had been chosen as the preferred bidder for the provision of a scheduled commercial air service to St Helena. A formal announcement on the contract award will be made once the contract negotiations are complete.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-11T16:35:40.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747623/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747623/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-03","St Helena: SA Airlink","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, when her Department expects that the air service contract between the St Helena Government and SA Airlink will be signed.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","2514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747624","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-11","<p>DFID is regular contact with both the Governor of St Helena and her team working on the air services procurement.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-11T16:34:53.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747624/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747624/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-03","St Helena: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether she has requested reports from the Governor of St Helena on the outcomes of the air service tender.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","2515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747625","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-11","<p>The tender process for the air services contract is managed by the St Helena Government. As that process is still on-going and is therefore subject to commercial confidentiality until completed, we are unable to provide the detail requested at this time.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-11T16:34:06.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747625/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747625/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-03","St Helena: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many responses the St Helena Government received on its tender for the air service.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","2516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747626","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-11","<p>DFID officials are in regular contact with the St Helena Government which leads the tender process for provision of a scheduled air service to St Helena. That process is ongoing and therefore meetings and discussions which have formed part of this process are subject to commercial confidentiality.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-11T16:34:36.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747626/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747626/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-03","SA Airlink","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what (a) discussions and (b) meetings her officials have had with SA Airlink on the future of the air service in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","2517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747627","Department for Education","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Department does not hold data on the number of applicants and applications to midwifery training courses. The information may be available from the Universities and Colleges Admissions Service (UCAS).</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-07-11T15:22:54.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747627/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747627/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-03","Midwives: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many (a) people applied and (b) applications were received for places on midwifery training courses by the January deadline in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","2510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747628","Department of Health","false","2017-07-11","<p>NHS Digital publishes workforce statistics and the following table shows the number of midwives who are 70 and over working in the National Health Service in England at 30 September 2012 to 2016. Data for March 2017 is also provided as this is the latest available.</p><p> </p><p>The data is headcount because equality data relates to individuals.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Hospital and Community Health Services (HCHS): Registered midwives who are 70 and and over in NHS trusts and clinical commissioning groups in England as at 30 September each specified year and latest data as at 31 March 2017.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Midwives age profile (headcount)</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>March-2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>70 and over</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>19</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: NHS Digital, Provisional NHS HCHS monthly workforce statistics.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-11T13:50:07.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747628/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747628/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-03","Midwives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many midwives working in the NHS in England were 70 or older in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","2484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747629","Department of Health","false","2017-07-11","<p>Information relating to the number of midwives in training has been collected annually by Health Education England since 2013. Prior to this, the information was collected from strategic health authorities.</p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the total number of midwives in formal training in England in each financial year from 2010/11 to 2016/17.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>5,644</p></td><td><p>5,955</p></td><td><p>6,315</p></td><td><p>6,413</p></td><td><p>6,662</p></td><td><p>6,350</p></td><td><p>6,559</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: From 2013/14 - Health Education England EdCom Analysis returns,</p><p>Pre 2013/14 Department of Health Financial Information Management System (FIMS)</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-11T13:56:42.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747629/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747629/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-03","Midwives: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many midwives have been in formal training in England in each six month period since 2010.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","2482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747630","Department of Health","false","2017-07-11","<p>NHS Digital publishes workforce statistics and the following table shows the age profile of midwives working in the National Health Service in England at 30 September 2012 to 2016. Data for March 2017 is also provided as this is the latest available.</p><p> </p><p>The data is headcount because equality data relates to individuals.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Hospital and Community Health Services (HCHS): Registered midwives by five year age band in NHS trusts and clinical commissioning groups in England as at 30 September each specified year and latest data as at 31 March 2017</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>March-2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Age profile of midwives (headcount)</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>24,765</p></td><td><p>25,006</p></td><td><p>25,333</p></td><td><p>25,418</p></td><td><p>25,466</p></td><td><p>26,081</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Under 25</p></td><td><p>1,000</p></td><td><p>1,136</p></td><td><p>1,159</p></td><td><p>1,156</p></td><td><p>1,149</p></td><td><p>1,387</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>25 to 29</p></td><td><p>2,218</p></td><td><p>2,421</p></td><td><p>2,677</p></td><td><p>2,949</p></td><td><p>3,205</p></td><td><p>3,400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>30 to 34</p></td><td><p>2,742</p></td><td><p>2,825</p></td><td><p>2,892</p></td><td><p>2,909</p></td><td><p>3,007</p></td><td><p>3,166</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>35 to 39</p></td><td><p>2,740</p></td><td><p>2,756</p></td><td><p>2,880</p></td><td><p>3,046</p></td><td><p>3,147</p></td><td><p>3,251</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>40 to 44</p></td><td><p>3,544</p></td><td><p>3,287</p></td><td>