"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747652","Department for Education","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Fulbright programme provides important opportunities for education exchanges between the UK and the US. We have received no communication from the US government to inform us of any proposal to cut funding of the Fulbright Programme.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-07-12T14:53:58.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747652/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747652/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-03","Scholarships: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what representations she has made to the US Administration about (a) the strategic importance of the Fulbright programme to the special relationship and (b) the need to preserve funding for the programme in the years ahead.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","2464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747653","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>Our officials are in contact with representatives from the Fulbright Commission. Decisions on the State Department budget are ultimately a matter for the US administration and Congress.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-10T13:18:56.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747653/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747653/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747653/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-03","USA: Scholarships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the US Administration on (a) the benefits of the Fulbright Scholarship programme to UK-US relations and (b) the level of funding required for that programme in the next five years.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","2463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747654","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-11","<p>Whether a person has “internet access” can be measured in different ways, for example whether their household has a fixed broadband connection, or whether they own a smartphone. However, I am not aware of any estimates of the proportion of people who have internet access by age group in each parliamentary constituency.</p><p>Ofcom’s “Adults' media use and attitudes” reports also set out estimates of different types of “internet access”, including by age, and geographical location, but not at constituency level.</p><p> </p><p>Fixed broadband infrastructure is almost universally available across the UK, and we are bringing in a Universal Service Obligation to ensure everyone in the UK has the right to request an affordable connection to broadband of a minimum specified speed, from a designated provider, no matter where they live or work, up to a reasonable cost threshold.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-11T12:03:10.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747654/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747654/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-03","Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate she has made of the proportion of people aged (a) 18 to 29, (b) 30 to 44, (c) 45 to 59, (d) 60 to 79 and (e) over 80-years old who have internet access in each parliamentary constituency.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","2495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747655","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government has made no such estimate. However, the Office for National Statistics compiles data on the activities carried out by people that use the internet, including internet banking. This can be found at http://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/householdcharacteristics/homeinternetandsocialmediausage/bulletins/internetaccesshouseholdsandindividuals/2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to improving access to financial services, across both traditional and digital channels. The Government also recognises the need to support local communities to adapt to changes in the banking landscape, including when bank branches close. In March 2015, the Government helped to broker an industry-wide agreement to work with customers and communities to minimise the impact of bank branch closures and put in place alternative banking services.</p><p> </p><p>The Government welcomed Professor Russel Griggs’ 2016 review of the Access to Banking Protocol and is pleased to see the industry commit to further improvements to protect those affected by closures.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-07-10T09:12:19.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747655/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747655/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-03","Bank Services: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the proportion of (a) 18 to 29, (b) 30 to 44, (c) 45 to 59, (d) 60 to 79 and (e) over 80 year olds  who use online banking in each parliamentary constituency.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","2496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747656","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Coroner’s report into Lakanal House recommended simplifying the fire safety guidance relating to Building Regulations (Approved Document B). This work was being progressed. Following the tragedy at Grenfell Tower, we will need to consider the position on guidance further alongside the Prime Minister’s commitment to look at wider issues.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-11T16:24:35.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747656/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747656/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-03","Fire Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the clarity of the guidance set out in paragraph 12.7 of Approved Document B on materials which can be used above and below 18 metres in high rise buildings.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","2474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747657","Department of Health","false","2017-07-07","<p>Next Steps on the Five Year Forward View described Accountable Care Systems (ACS) as an ‘evolved’ version of a Sustainability and Transformation Partnership (STP), working as a locally integrated health system. Simon Stevens announced at the NHS Confederation Conference that nine areas, covering eight STPs, would become ACSs in the first wave.</p><p> </p><p>STPs have previously engaged with patients and the public on their plans for the local area, and local engagement continues to play a key part in the development of the footprint. As ACSs are established, we expect that local engagement will continue to play a fundamental part in the development process.</p><p> </p><p>No significant changes to the services people currently receive will be made without local engagement and, where required, consultation. There are longstanding assurance processes in place to make sure this happens.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-07-07T10:08:55.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747657/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747657/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-03","Accountable Care Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to ensure that (a) patients and (b) the public are consulted on the creation of Accountable Care Systems.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","2542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747658","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Coroner’s report into Lakanal House recommended simplifying the fire safety guidance relating to Building Regulations (Approved Document B). This work was being progressed. Following the tragedy at Grenfell Tower, we will need to consider the position on guidance further alongside the Prime Minister’s commitment to look at wider issues.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-11T16:25:04.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747658/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747658/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-03","Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans his Department has to amend the Building Regulations and the guidance contained in Approved Document B on fire safety.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","2543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747659","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-11","<p>On the 30 June 2017, we published a note that sets out the immediate actions that landlords should be taking if it is determined that the insulation with Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) is unlikely to be compliant with current Building Regulations guidance. That note can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/explanatory-note-on-safety-checks-and-testing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/explanatory-note-on-safety-checks-and-testing</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-11T16:20:59.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747659/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747659/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-03","High Rise Flats: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department is giving to local authorities on the removal of cladding from high-rise buildings.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","2450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747660","Home Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>Discussions with the US Administration on their proposals for the pre-clearance in the UK of passengers travelling to the US for immigration purposes are ongoing. No decision has yet been made.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-10T13:04:11.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747660/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747660/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Immigration Controls: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress has been made on discussions with the US Administration on allowing the pre-clearance in the UK of passengers for immigration purposes.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","2451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747661","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-18","<p>The UK currently has nearly 400 Armed Forces personnel deployed in South Sudan. As requested by the United Nations (UN), UK troops have deployed to support the UN Mission in South Sudan by carrying out engineering and medical roles at the UN camps in Malakal and Bentiu. They will work to improve the delivery of the UN mission, and are a demonstration of the UK's commitment to UN operations.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-07-18T13:26:34.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747661/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747661/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-03","South Sudan: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many members of the armed forces are currently working in South Sudan; and what role those people are performing.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","2386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747662","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-18","<p>Working with international partners, the UK Government has been instrumental in agreeing a tougher approach to deliberate restrictions on humanitarian access by the Government of South Sudan, which sets out clearly the consequences of violations against aid workers. We ensure UK Aid is effective by working through a range of UN and international organisations who are experienced in operating in South Sudan, who are able to work across the country, and who can deliver flexibly according to need.</p><p>The UK continues to provide humanitarian assistance in South Sudan, where half the population is in need. This year we will provide a package of lifesaving support that includes reaching over 500,000 people with food assistance, providing safe drinking water for more than 300,000 people, and providing emergency health services for more than 100,000 people.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-18T16:11:04.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747662/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747662/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-03","South Sudan: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to ensure that humanitarian assistance can be delivered effectively in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","2387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747663","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-18","<p>We are deeply concerned about the human rights abuses in South Sudan, especially in the area of sexual violence. The 2015 Peace Agreement mandated the creation of a Hybrid Court in South Sudan for the most serious of crimes. We understand that the African Union has been working on a proposal for such a court and now needs to discuss this with the Government of South Sudan. We urge all parties to accelerate the establishment of the Court. We have jointly led a resolution at the Human Rights Council in Geneva which extended the mandate of the South Sudan Human Rights Commission to gather evidence of crimes for eventual use in a court of law.</p><p>We continue to urge all sides to show restraint, bring an end to the violence in South Sudan, and return to an inclusive and peaceful political process.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-18T08:38:36.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747663/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747663/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-03","South Sudan: Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on progress on the creation of the Hybrid Court in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","2385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747664","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The modus operandi of the coordination committee will need to be agreed between the Conservative party and the Democratic Unionist party. It will be attended by members of the Conservative Party and the DUP to support the agreement made between the two parties.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-07-10T14:25:25.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747664/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747664/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-03","Coordination Committee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will extend the membership of the Coordination Committee to be established between the Government and the Democratic Unionist Party to the hon. Member for North Down.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","2657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747665","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-06","<p>I wrote to the political parties in January seeking their views on this issue and, while there was broad support for the future publication of donations and loans, only one party expressed support for backdating publication to 1 January 2014. Having considered the representations of the parties, I did not believe it right to impose retrospective regulations on those who donated in accordance with the rules set out in law at the time. The secondary legislation to give effect to full transparency which I propose would therefore apply to donations and loans received on or after 1 July 2017.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","2666","2017-07-06T16:39:07.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747665/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747665/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-03","Political Parties: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, for what reasons he declined the request of the Electoral Commission to publish the details of donations since January 2014 to political parties operating in Northern Ireland; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","2662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747666","Leader of the House","false","2017-07-11","<p>Short Money is not available to parties whose Members have not sworn the oath. Instead, Representative Money is available to those parties so that they may carry out their representative duties.</p><p>Further information about Representative Money is available at http://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/SN01663/SN01663.pdf.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-07-11T16:16:48.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747666/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747666/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-07-03","Sinn Fein: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, whether hon. Members elected for Sinn Fein receive any monies in funding analogous to Short Money provision to the Democratic Unionist Party.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","2658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747667","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-21","<p>The modus operandi of the coordination committee will need to be agreed between the Conservative party and the Democratic Unionist party.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-07-21T15:05:10.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747667/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747667/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-03","Coordination Committee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to ensure publication of the minutes of meetings of the co-ordination committee to be established in accordance with the confidence and supply deal agreed on 26 June 2017 between the Democratic Unionist Party and the Government; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","2663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747668","Leader of the House","false","2017-07-11","<p>I refer the hon. Lady to the answer that was given to the hon. Member for West Bromwich East on Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-06-28/1655/" target="_blank">1655</a>. This was answered Monday 3rd July.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-07-11T16:20:15.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747668/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747668/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-07-03","Democratic Unionist Party: Short Money","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what estimate she has made of the amount of Short Money that the Democratic Unionist Party will receive as a result of the outcome of the June 2017 General Election.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","2659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747669","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The terms of the deal between the Conservative party and the DUP have been set out in the agreement.</p><p>The rules about transparency of political donations are set out in the Political Parties, Elections and Referendums Act 2000. The Government intends to bring forward legislation to extend transparency that already exists for political parties in Great Britain to also cover donations and loans received by Northern Ireland parties on or after 1 July 2017.</p><p><strong></strong><br><br></p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-07-10T14:20:43.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747669/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747669/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-03","Political Parties: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether ending the anonymity of political donations to parties in Northern Ireland was discussed with the Democratic Unionist Party (DUP) before the deal was signed between the Government and the DUP on 26 June 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","2664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747670","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The modus operandi of the coordination committee will be agreed between the Conservative party and the Democratic Unionist party. It will be attended by members of the Conservative Party and the DUP to support the agreement made between the two parties.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-07-10T14:27:18.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747670/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747670/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-03","Coordination Committee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the (a) composition and (b) frequency of meetings is of the Co-ordination Committee agreed to be established on 26 June 2017 in the confidence and supply deal agreed between the Democratic Unionist Party and the Government; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","2660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747671","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-06","<p>The reporting of political donations and loans is overseen by the Electoral Commission. The Conservative Party is under an obligation to declare all reportable donations and loans to the Electoral Commission.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-07-06T16:40:35.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747671/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747671/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-03","Conservative Party: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps he is taking to ensure that the Conservative Party publishes details of the donations made since January 2014 to the Conservative Party operating in Northern Ireland; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","2665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747672","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Coordination Committee will be established to support the political agreement made between the Conservative party and the Democratic Unionist party.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-07-10T14:26:33.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747672/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747672/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-03","Coordination Committee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the constitutional status of the Co-ordination Committee to be established between the Government and the Democratic Unionist Party in accordance with the deal agreed between them on 26 June 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","2661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747673","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-06","<p>I wrote to the political parties in January seeking their views on this issue and, while there was broad support for the future publication of donations and loans, only one party expressed support for backdating publication to 1 January 2014. Having considered the representations of the parties, I did not believe it right to impose retrospective regulations on those who donated in accordance with the rules set out in law at the time. The secondary legislation to give effect to full transparency which I propose would therefore apply to donations and loans received on or after 1 July 2017.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","2662","2017-07-06T16:39:07.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747673/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747673/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-03","Political Parties: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, for what reasons he did not make retrospective to January 2014 the end of anonymity for political donations to parties in Northern Ireland during his statement to the House of 3 July 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","2666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747675","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>Ministerial visits are under constant review. The British Consulate General in Hong Kong continues to support and represent UK interests there.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-07-10T12:54:15.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747675/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747675/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-03","Hong Kong: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the new Minister for Asia plans to visit Hong Kong during the current Parliamentary session.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","2372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747676","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>I had a meeting with the Chinese Ambassador on 5 July. I discussed the strong bilateral relationship between the UK and China, and the importance of Hong Kong's 'One Country, Two Systems' as the basis for its continued success. I made clear the British Government's commitment to the Joint Declaration on Hong Kong, which is a formal Treaty between China and the UK. This declaration, registered with the UN, remains in force until July 2047. As a consequence, I did not accept the Chinese government's position that this was purely an historical document. Furthermore, as a guarantor of the Joint Declaration, the British Government also regards it as legitimate that it continues to issue a six-monthly report to the House on Hong Kong affairs.</p><p>To mark the 20th anniversary of the establishment of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, the Foreign Secretary issued a Written Ministerial Statement to the House on 29 June (<a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statements/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statements/</a>).</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-07-11T15:59:36.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747676/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747676/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-03","Hong Kong: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Chinese counterpart on the 20th anniversary of the handover of Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","2373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747677","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>​I have no immediate plans to meet Rt Hon. Lord Patten of Barnes, and he has not requested a meeting.</p><p>I held a meeting with the Chinese Ambassador on 5 July in which I made clear that the British Government did not accept the position of the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs spokesperson that the Joint Declaration was an historical document of no practical significance. I stressed that on this basis, as a guarantor of the Joint Declaration, and the principle of 'one country, two system', the British Government regarded it as legitimate to continue to issue a six-monthly report to Parliament on Hong Kong affairs.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-07-11T16:01:59.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747677/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747677/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-03","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to meet Lord Patten of Barnes to discuss the democratic situation in Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","2374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747678","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>In 2015, the Department For International Development commissioned an assessment of climate change and its likely impact on many of the Overseas Territories. The report is available on the gov.uk website. Separate work is underway with those territory governments not covered by this report, to ensure measures are in place.</p><p>To assist our Overseas Territories (OT) to protect their biodiversity, financial support is provided by the Government, through the Darwin Plus initiative and the Conflict, Security and Stability Fund (CSSF). Darwin Plus helps UK Overseas Territories to protect their biodiversity and meet their international obligations under key biodiversity conventions. To date, 70 Darwin Plus projects, with a total value of £10.9 million, have been funded.</p><p>Through the CSSF the Government has provided £2.02m to assist the OTs in embedding natural capital considerations into decision-making and planning; £1m to support Territories in improving their biosecurity; £1.75m to support the work led by the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds to tackle invasive species in and restore Gough Island; and £4.8m during the current financial year to support the development and implementation of a blue belt of marine protected areas around the OTs.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-10T15:46:07.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747678/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747678/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-03","British Overseas Territories: Biodiversity and Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the effects of climate change on Overseas Territories; and what measures are being put in place to protect biodiversity in Overseas Territories.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","2446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747679","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>​Ministerial visits are under constant review. The British Consulate General in Hong Kong continues to support and represent UK interests there.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-07-10T12:55:33.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747679/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747679/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-03","Hong Kong: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to visit Hong Kong during this parliamentary session.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","2447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747680","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-06","<p>The information requested cannot be released as individuals may be identifiable. The Department for Exiting the European Union is committed to the creation of a diverse and inclusive working environment to ensure staff do not face any barriers to success, and all staff feel supported at work.</p><p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has released information on the UK's negotiating team which is publicly available on gov.uk. This outlines the core negotiating team however departments are also building up their capacity in their own areas of responsibility. DExEU is drawing together expertise from a wide range of departments where there is specific relevant knowledge.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-06T16:02:56.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747680/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747680/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-03","Department for Exiting the European Union: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many of his senior negotiating team are from an ethnic minority background.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","2609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747681","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-06","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has released information on the UK's negotiating team which is publicly available on gov.uk. This outlines the core negotiating team however departments are also building up their capacity in their own areas of responsibility.</p><p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is committed to the creation of a diverse and inclusive working environment to ensure staff do not face any barriers to success, and all staff feel supported at work. As such, the Department is committed to the steps established in the 2016 Talent Action Plan to help the Civil Service become the most inclusive employer in the UK. The department is also committed to working with a diverse range of external organisations, to ensure our work reflects a broad range of opinions across the UK.We will ensure we have the right skills to get the best deal for the UK.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-06T16:01:49.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747681/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747681/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-03","Department for Exiting the European Union: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 26 June 2017 to Question 160, whether he plans to increase the number of women in his senior negotiating team.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","2610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747682","Home Office","false","2017-07-06","<p>The Government’s top priority is the safety and security of the public. We have protected Counter-Terrorism police spend in real terms over the Spending Review period and invested in counter-terrorism policing to grow key capabilities, including providing £144m to increase armed policing capability.</p><p>Funding for counter-terrorism policing is announced to Parliament ahead of the beginning of each financial year. The settlement for 2017-18 was published in a Written Ministerial Statement on 1 February 2017. Funding for 2018-19 will be announced in due course.</p><p>To reflect how we fight terrorism in the 21<sup>st</sup> century we have increased total spending on CT across Government by 30% from the planned comprehensive spending review £11.7bn to £15.2bn meaning more money for our Intelligence service, police and other agencies.</p><p> </p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-07-06T16:30:24.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747682/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747682/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Counter-terrorism: Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the potential effect on public safety of decreasing the Counter Terrorism Policing and Protective Security Grant by 7.2 per cent in cash terms over the next two years.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","2404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747683","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>Government is committed to building the resilience and independence of smaller charities. The Office for Civil Society in England are providing a multi-year programme of fundraising training and support.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to improving public service outcomes by ensuring that small charities are able to compete for commissioned grants and contracts. This is why in December 2016, we announced the public services programme to strengthen the role of civil society organisations in the public service markets. We are continuing to work with local authority, voluntary sector and cross-government stakeholders to prepare for delivery of this programme.</p><p> </p><p>Our vision is of a confident and capable sector, with the ability to raise funds from diverse sources. By increasing their long term sustainability, small charities can continue their vital role in helping to build a stronger society.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","2472 ; 2473","2017-07-10T16:46:13.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747683/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747683/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-03","Charities: Fund Raising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the potential long-term effect of providing financial support to smaller charities for fundraising training and support.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747684","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>Government is committed to building the resilience and independence of smaller charities. The Office for Civil Society in England are providing a multi-year programme of fundraising training and support.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to improving public service outcomes by ensuring that small charities are able to compete for commissioned grants and contracts. This is why in December 2016, we announced the public services programme to strengthen the role of civil society organisations in the public service markets. We are continuing to work with local authority, voluntary sector and cross-government stakeholders to prepare for delivery of this programme.</p><p> </p><p>Our vision is of a confident and capable sector, with the ability to raise funds from diverse sources. By increasing their long term sustainability, small charities can continue their vital role in helping to build a stronger society.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","2471 ; 2473","2017-07-10T16:46:13.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747684/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747684/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-03","Charities: Fund Raising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with (a) Cabinet colleagues and (b) local authorities on support provided to smaller charities to raise funds through grants and commissioning processes.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747685","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>Government is committed to building the resilience and independence of smaller charities. The Office for Civil Society in England are providing a multi-year programme of fundraising training and support.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to improving public service outcomes by ensuring that small charities are able to compete for commissioned grants and contracts. This is why in December 2016, we announced the public services programme to strengthen the role of civil society organisations in the public service markets. We are continuing to work with local authority, voluntary sector and cross-government stakeholders to prepare for delivery of this programme.</p><p> </p><p>Our vision is of a confident and capable sector, with the ability to raise funds from diverse sources. By increasing their long term sustainability, small charities can continue their vital role in helping to build a stronger society.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","2471 ; 2472","2017-07-10T16:46:13.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747685/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747685/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-03","Charities: Fund Raising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with charity-sector bodies and foundations on support provided to smaller charities for fundraising activities.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747686","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-10","<p>As stated in the Government’s Transformation Strategy and the Conservative Manifesto, this government is committed to providing services that are digital by default - reducing paper and manual processing, reducing cost and improving user satisfaction.</p><p>BEIS is actively working with all its Arm’s Length Bodies, internal teams and contracted service providers to reduce the amount of paper processing by delivering services digitally wherever possible. There will always be some exceptions where, for legal reasons, paper processing is required but we will continue to explore how new technologies can overcome these barriers and implement them as soon as possible.</p><p>Some examples of what the BEIS Group has already delivered or are in the process of delivering include:</p><p>Land Registry has developed a new Local Land Charge Register Service to digitise existing paper records from 326 Local Authorities and migrate them to a single national Local Land Charge register. This will improve resilience, improve the customer experience of using this service and introduce standardise fees.</p><p>The Innovation Funding Service has developed a new digital service to replace a previously paper based process to submit online applications for research and development funding. Innovate UK run approximately 100 competitions per year and receives in excess of 4,000 applications.</p><p>Finally, the Intellectual Property Office has designed a new digital service that enables customers to apply for a patent design online. This includes the implementation of a new back office system that will deliver a more efficient, cost effective service that will lower operating costs and reduce the fees for customers registering a design.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-10T16:00:52.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747686/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747686/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747687","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The government is committed to providing services that are digital by default - reducing paper and manual processing, reducing cost and improving user satisfaction.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government Digital Service (GDS), part of the Cabinet Office, leads government in transforming services based around user needs, reducing reliance on paper-based systems and saving money for the taxpayer.</p><p><strong></strong><br><br></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-10T16:13:28.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747687/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747687/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-03","Cabinet Office: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747688","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-11","<p>The government continues to encourage more people to go online, so they can access the guidance and services they need – as well as reducing the cost of public services. The department has continued to reduce its paper consumption. This has been achieved through better print facilities and a continuing programme of IT improvements which are helping to decrease our reliance on paper.</p><p>The department seeks to digitise wherever possible and actively works with partners across government to adhere to best practice in its media and external communications and forms.</p><p>Details of the department’s performance in reducing its paper consumption were published in the Greening Government Commitments Annual Report – April 2015 to March 2016 on 20 April 2017.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/greening-government-commitments-2015-to-2016-annual-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/greening-government-commitments-2015-to-2016-annual-report</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-11T12:46:38.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747688/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747688/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-03","Department for Communities and Local Government: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747689","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-11","<p>The government is committed to providing services that are digital by default - reducing paper and manual processing, reducing cost and improving user satisfaction.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-11T12:54:26.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747689/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747689/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-03","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747690","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Ministry of Defence is committed to reducing its paper-based processes by digitising these where possible. The Department is committed to delivering the Government Transformation Strategy and, in February 2017, published the Defence Information Strategy highlighting its strategic objectives to deliver user-centric digital services.</p><p>Work to identify where manual processes exist and explore opportunities to digitise them is ongoing across the Department. For example, as part of the transformation of our Defence Business Services organisation, a Forms Digitisation project is seeking to automate as many paper forms as possible in order to reduce manual processing and improve the experience for the end user.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-07-10T15:51:14.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747690/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747690/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-03","Ministry of Defence: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747691","Department for Education","false","2017-07-14","<p>The government continues to encourage more people to go online, so they can access the guidance and services they need – as well as reducing the cost of public services. The department has continued to reduce its paper consumption. This has been achieved through better print facilities and a continuing programme of IT improvements, such as the Digital Apprenticeship Service, which are helping to decrease our reliance on paper</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-14T10:51:19.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747691/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747691/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-03","Department for Education: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747692","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Digital Transformation Programme is targeting the redevelopment and improvement of key Defra services to make them easier for customers to interact with the department, and to make cost efficiencies through the use of more modern and flexible technology that is better able to support Defra's services through changing requirements. Different areas of work within the Programme are looking at different services provided by Defra, most of which are already online. However, there are a number of projects and work streams which will deliver reductions of the amount of manual processing on paper. These include:</p><p> </p><p>- Farm Services Management: through the roll-out of a new scheduling and data capture tool which, in conjunction with new mobile devices, will reduce the amount of paper-recording by APHA inspectors.</p><p>- Animal Disease Testing Service: which provides a digital alternative to written requests from Vets for disease tests for animals.</p><p>- Fishing Rod Licenses: by providing an easier digital application process, so reducing the proportions of requests through telephone or over-the-counter channels.</p><p> </p><p>These are important benefits of the Digital Transformation Programme. But the main focus of the Programme is to replace old systems with newer ones that are more cost effective and easier for customers to use.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-07-11T11:50:09.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747692/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747692/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-03","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747693","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-11","<p>The government is committed to providing services that are digital by default - reducing paper and manual processing, reducing cost and improving user satisfaction.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-11T14:21:04.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747693/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747693/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-03","Department for Exiting the European Union: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747694","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) is committed to moving paper-based services to digital or online services where this delivers efficiencies and provides simpler, secure services.</p><p>For example, the FCO has made significant progress in digitising consular services and reducing the time it takes to issue Emergency Travel Documents.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-11T17:00:00.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747694/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747694/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-03","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747695","Department of Health","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Department is committed to providing digital services and delivering on the Government’s sustainability targets. This includes measures taken to reduce printing and manual processing on paper. We have introduced a managed print service and have replaced old printers with fast, modern, multi-functional Xerox devices. These provide “Follow me” capability which releases print copies only when collected thus reducing paper wastage, cutting printing costs and reducing the risk of information being misplaced.</p><p> </p><p>The Department routinely uses digital technologies to manage information electronically including online performance appraisals, sickness absence and pay slips, and the digital processing of procurement and purchasing, invoicing and correspondence. File sharing and publishing are carried out via digital channels including Cloud services. Plans are in place to further digitise departmental business processes and improve access to online management information in 2018.</p><p> </p><p>By the end of the summer the Department will also have move to a fully mobile device enabled workforce, which supported by corporate wifi services will see all Departmental staff able access digital services and perform transactions digitally on internal and external systems.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-11T13:54:36.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747695/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747695/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-03","Department of Health: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747696","Home Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The government continues to encourage more people to go online, so they can access the guidance and services they need – as well as reducing the cost of public services. The department has continued to reduce its paper consumption. This has been achieved through a revised print strategy and a continuing programme of IT improvements, such as Access UK (a single online Immigration application service for UK-based and international customers) which are helping to decrease our reliance on paper.</p><p> </p><p>Details of the department’s performance in reducing its paper consumption were published in the Greening Government Commitments Annual Report – April 2015 to March 2016 on 20 April 2017.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/greening-government-commitments-2015-to-2016-annual-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/greening-government-commitments-2015-to-2016-annual-report</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-10T16:17:36.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747696/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747696/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Home Office: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747697","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-07","<p>Management of aid programmes, including procurement and payments, is managed through electronic systems. In addition, corporate support functions for managing staff and facilities management are also undertaken on electronic systems. There are a limited number of processes where use of paper is required.</p><p>DFID will continue to review processes and use evolving digital technology to reduce manual processing on paper.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-07T15:07:24.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747697/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747697/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-03","Department for International Development: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747698","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Department for International Trade aims to ensure that the primary route for export or investment support is digital. The Department continues to develop and extend the reach of digital services through great.gov.uk. Technology used by staff is also being upgraded to enable the use of cloud-based software that promotes simultaneous collaboration and seamless mobile working, and further drive productivity. The Digital team are also developing a new business relationship management system, which will encourage and enable staff to record business interactions digitally.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-07-11T15:07:14.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747698/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747698/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-03","Department for International Trade: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747699","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-11","<p>The government continues to encourage more people to go online, so they can access the guidance and services they need – as well as reducing the cost of public services. Through our Digital transformation programme within HMCTS, and MoJ’s Transformation programme which introduces more mobile IT devices we have reduced our reliance on paper. The use of the Crown Court Digital Case System has saved us from printing over 40 million pages of information, reducing the amount of classified waste produced.</p><p> </p><p>Details of the department’s performance in reducing its paper consumption were published in the Greening Government Commitments Annual Report – April 2015 to March 2016 on 20 April 2017:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/greening-government-commitments-2015-to-2016-annual-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/greening-government-commitments-2015-to-2016-annual-report</a></p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-07-11T15:27:56.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747699/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747699/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-03","Ministry of Justice: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747700","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Department has aligned its Digital Strategy with the Government Digital Strategy and the Government Transformation Strategy.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-07-11T16:10:38.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747700/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747700/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-03","Department for Transport: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747701","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-11","<p>The government is committed to providing services that are digital by default - reducing paper and manual processing, reducing cost and improving user satisfaction. HM Treasury is currently reducing the manual processing of paper in finance and HR processes as part of a project to replace our Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) system.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-07-11T14:10:04.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747701/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747701/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-03","Treasury: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747702","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>In DWP, digital tools are being deployed across the organisation that are supporting new ways of working including the reduction and reliance on printing and associated costs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We have the following spend data for Office copier paper:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17* to March 2017 </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£2,543,643</p></td><td><p>£2,173,328</p></td><td><p>£1,670,000</p></td><td><p>£1,400,000</p></td><td><p>£1,011,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-11T15:40:37.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747702/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747702/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-03","Department for Work and Pensions: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the amount of manual processing on paper that it carries out and to make such processing digital.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","2604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747703","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-06","<p>In its Answer of 18 April 2017 to Question 69488, the Government stated that it was conducting research on the effects of transparency in overseas money transfers (involving foreign exchange), on consumer decisions. This research will help to inform the Government's response to the consultation on draft regulations for the implementation of the Second Payment Services Directive. This response will be published shortly.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-07-06T07:26:43.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747703/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747703/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-03","Foreign Exchange: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 18 April 2017 to Question 69488, if he will place in the Library the results of the research commissioned by his Department on the effect of current pricing structures used by foreign exchange providers on consumer value choices.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","2375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747704","Home Office","false","2017-07-06","<p>The Supreme Court judgment in MM (Lebanon) &amp; Others upheld the lawfulness under the European Convention on Human Rights of the minimum income requirement for partner visas. We are carefully considering what the Supreme Court said in relation to cases involving children and to exceptional cases where the minimum income requirement has not been met. We will make a further announcement in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-06T14:44:31.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747704/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747704/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Immigration: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when her Department plans to publish new Immigration Rules and associated Guidance in response to the ruling in the Supreme Court case of MM & Ors v SSHD (2017).","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","2402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747705","Home Office","false","2017-07-06","<p>We remain committed to resettling 20,000 vulnerable refugees from Syria by 2020, as announced by the then Prime Minister in 2015. We are on track to deliver this commitment. We will continue to rely on UNHCR to identify and refer the most vulnerable refugees who have fled the Syrian conflict and cannot return to their country of origin, whatever their nationality.</p><p> </p><p>Resettlement is only one strand of our efforts in the region, and is complemented by the UK’s significant humanitarian aid programme and our diplomatic efforts to end the conflict. We believe this approach is the best way to ensure that the UK’s help has the greatest impact for the majority of refugees who remain in the region and their host countries.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-06T14:41:44.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747705/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747705/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Written Statement of 3 July 2017, Official Report, WS 23, if the Government will increase the number of refugees to be resettled under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","2647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747706","Home Office","false","2017-07-06","<p>The extended scope of the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme will make it accessible to the most vulnerable refugees in the MENA region who have fled the Syrian conflict, regardless of their nationality. This may include individuals who are Palestinian and stateless, if they are genuine refugees and cannot seek the protection of their country of origin.</p><p>We will continue to rely on UNHCR to identify and refer the most vulnerable refugees but will no longer limit the scheme solely to those with Syrian nationality.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-06T14:43:03.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747706/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747706/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Written Statement of 3 July 2017, Official Report, WS 23, whether it is her policy that refugees who are (a) Palestinian and (b) stateless will eligible to be resettled in the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","2648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747707","Department of Health","false","2017-07-06","<p>NHS England and NHS Improvement have advised that this information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Clinical commissioning groups and NHS England are responsible for awarding and holding contracts with providers for the services that they have a responsibility to commission.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","2532","2017-07-06T15:10:09.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747707/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747707/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747707/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-03","Health Services: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many clinical services contracts awarded to private providers in England are of a duration of longer than five years.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","2531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747708","Department of Health","false","2017-07-06","<p>NHS England and NHS Improvement have advised that this information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Clinical commissioning groups and NHS England are responsible for awarding and holding contracts with providers for the services that they have a responsibility to commission.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","2531","2017-07-06T15:10:09.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747708/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747708/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747708/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-03","Health Services: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the (a) median and (b) average length in years is of clinical service contracts awarded to private providers in England.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","2532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747709","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-06","<p>The government’s manifesto committed to create a UK Shared Prosperity Fund. Further details will be set out in due course. The government has provided a guarantee for all European Structural and Investment Fund projects signed before the UK leaves the European Union (EU) if they provide good value for money and are in line with domestic strategic priorities. This includes projects that continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","2384","2017-07-06T15:30:09.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747709/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747709/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-03","Prosperity Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much funding will be available through the UK Shared Prosperity Fund; and what mechanism will be used to distribute that funding.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","2380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747710","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-06","<p>Across England we are making huge strides towards rebalancing the economy and empowering local government. On 4 May, the first six city region mayors were elected for Greater Manchester, the West Midlands, Liverpool City Region, Tees Valley, the West of England and Cambridgeshire and Peterborough – representing 9.8 million people in England. We remain committed to our ambitious devolution deal with Sheffield City Region, comprising the local authority areas of Barnsley, Doncaster, Rotherham, and Sheffield. The mayoral election will take place in May 2018. Against this background, we intend to have early meetings with local businesses and political leaders, as it is important to agree a separate deal which includes West Yorkshire.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-07-06T11:39:51.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747710/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747710/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-03","Devolution: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the Government's policy is on a devolved settlement for Yorkshire.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","2381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747711","Department for Education","false","2017-07-07","<p>The Department for Education welcomes the Commission’s report, published on 28 June, which considers efforts to improve social mobility over the last twenty years. The Commission rightly concludes that too often life chances can be determined, not by effort and talents, but where you come from, who your parents are and what school you attended. The Department will set out further details on policy to tackle this social injustice in due course.</p><p> </p><p>Thanks to the Government’s reforms, there are 1.8 million more pupils in good or outstanding schools than in 2010, and we are delivering three million apprenticeship places, opening up access to our higher education system and investing £500 million a year into technical education.</p><p> </p><p>However, we want to go further. The Social Mobility Commission’s previous analysis has contributed to our understanding of the geography of social mobility, and last year we launched our £72 million Opportunity Areas programme. This brings together local businesses, schools and councils in 12 social mobility ‘coldspots’ to create better opportunities for young people. By working with these Opportunity Areas, identified by the Commission, we aim to better understand how we can address the barriers to social mobility from the early years to adulthood.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","2383","2017-07-07T13:51:19.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747711/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747711/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747711/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-03","Social Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the recommendations in the Social Mobility Commission's report, entitled The Time for Change, published 28 June 2017, what plans she has to develop and implement a new social mobility test for public policy.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","2382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747712","Department for Education","false","2017-07-07","<p>The Department for Education welcomes the Commission’s report, published on 28 June, which considers efforts to improve social mobility over the last twenty years. The Commission rightly concludes that too often life chances can be determined, not by effort and talents, but where you come from, who your parents are and what school you attended. The Department will set out further details on policy to tackle this social injustice in due course.</p><p> </p><p>Thanks to the Government’s reforms, there are 1.8 million more pupils in good or outstanding schools than in 2010, and we are delivering three million apprenticeship places, opening up access to our higher education system and investing £500 million a year into technical education.</p><p> </p><p>However, we want to go further. The Social Mobility Commission’s previous analysis has contributed to our understanding of the geography of social mobility, and last year we launched our £72 million Opportunity Areas programme. This brings together local businesses, schools and councils in 12 social mobility ‘coldspots’ to create better opportunities for young people. By working with these Opportunity Areas, identified by the Commission, we aim to better understand how we can address the barriers to social mobility from the early years to adulthood.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","2382","2017-07-07T13:51:19.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747712/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747712/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747712/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-03","Social Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the recommendations in the Social Mobility Commission's report, entitled The Time for Change, published 28 June 2017, what plans she has to develop a strategic cross-departmental social mobility plan.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","2383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747713","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-06","<p>The government’s manifesto committed to create a UK Shared Prosperity Fund. Further details will be set out in due course. The government has provided a guarantee for all European Structural and Investment Fund projects signed before the UK leaves the European Union (EU) if they provide good value for money and are in line with domestic strategic priorities. This includes projects that continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","2380","2017-07-06T15:30:09.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747713/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747713/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747713/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-03","Prosperity Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the UK Shared Prosperity Fund will be allocated on the basis of a formula or following a bidding process.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","2384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747714","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government is determined that insurers should treat customers fairly and firms are required to do so under the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) rules. The FCA sets the conduct standards required of insurance firms which aim to ensure consumers are treated fairly. This includes ensuring fair access to insurance products for all consumers.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor has discussed the Grenfell tower disaster with leading industry representatives to get an understanding of how they may respond, and any possible impact on insurance for residents. The industry have said that it is too early to properly understand the implications, so have not yet made any changes to their underwriting models or pricing strategies.</p><p> </p><p>The Treasury has also been in contact with the relevant insurance companies reported to have refused home insurance for residents living in tower blocks. Both companies have assured officials that no individuals in the tower blocks have been refused access to home insurance as a result of the fire at Grenfell Tower, but we remain in regular contact with the insurance industry to understand how it may shape their view of fire risk. The Treasury will continue to monitor the situation and will investigate this matter further if it sees evidence of customers in tower blocks being treated unfairly.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","2498","2017-07-10T09:09:58.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747714/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747714/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747714/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-03","Insurance: High Rise Flats","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the insurance industry on insurance for residents of tower blocks.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","2497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747715","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government is determined that insurers should treat customers fairly and firms are required to do so under the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) rules. The FCA sets the conduct standards required of insurance firms which aim to ensure consumers are treated fairly. This includes ensuring fair access to insurance products for all consumers.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor has discussed the Grenfell tower disaster with leading industry representatives to get an understanding of how they may respond, and any possible impact on insurance for residents. The industry have said that it is too early to properly understand the implications, so have not yet made any changes to their underwriting models or pricing strategies.</p><p> </p><p>The Treasury has also been in contact with the relevant insurance companies reported to have refused home insurance for residents living in tower blocks. Both companies have assured officials that no individuals in the tower blocks have been refused access to home insurance as a result of the fire at Grenfell Tower, but we remain in regular contact with the insurance industry to understand how it may shape their view of fire risk. The Treasury will continue to monitor the situation and will investigate this matter further if it sees evidence of customers in tower blocks being treated unfairly.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","2497","2017-07-10T09:09:58.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747715/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747715/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747715/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-03","House Insurance: High Rise Flats","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of whether residents of tower blocks are encountering difficulties in renewing their home insurance after the Grenfell Tower fire.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","2498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747716","Department of Health","false","2017-07-11","<p>The table below shows counts of finished admission episodes (FAEs) with an external cause of assault by corrosive substance, for each year since 2012 in England.</p><p> </p><p>Counts of FAEs with an external cause of assault by corrosive substance, 2012-13 to 2015-16 activity in England</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>FAEs</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>97</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>109</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>106</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>98</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Hospital Episode Statistics, NHS Digital</p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><p>1. A FAE is the first period of admitted patient care under one consultant within one healthcare provider. FAEs are counted against the year or month in which the admission episode finishes. Admissions do not represent the number of patients, as a person may have more than one admission within the period.</p><p> </p><p>2. Activity in English National Health Service hospitals and English NHS commissioned activity in the independent sector.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-11T13:47:47.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747716/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747716/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747716/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-03","Crimes of Violence: Corrosive Substances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many hospital admissions in England were categorized as assault by corrosive substance in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","2366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747717","Home Office","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Home Office is working closely with the National Police Chiefs’ Council to get a better understanding of the scale and nature of acid and other corrosive attacks.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-12T15:21:12.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747717/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747717/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747717/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Crimes of Violence: Acids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans her Department has to collect and collate statistics on the age and gender of perpetrators of acid attacks.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","2361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747718","Home Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Home Office does not specifically collect data from police forces on acid and other corrosive attacks as part of its regular data collection. Acid and other corrosive attacks resulting in injury are included in Office for National Statistics published statistics within assault with injury offences and assault with intent to cause serious harm offences, but cannot be disaggregated. We are working closely with the National Police Chiefs’ Council to get a better understanding of the scale and nature of acid and other corrosive attacks.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-11T15:23:27.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747718/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747718/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747718/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Crimes of Violence: Acids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many incidents of acid attacks resulted in prosecutions in each of the last five years; and what steps she is taking to improve the reporting of acid attacks.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","2362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747719","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-06","<p>Enforcement statistics for the 2016/17 reporting year will be made available in due course.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-06T14:33:10.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747719/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747719/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747719/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03","Minimum Wage: Unpaid Taxes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the total sum of arrears recovered by HM Revenue and Customs was for non-compliance with the national minimum wage in 2016-17; how many (a) workers and (b) employers those arrears relate to; how much of that total sum of arrears was recovered through the self-correction mechanism introduced in 2015; and how many (i) workers and (ii) employers those self-corrected arrears relate to.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","2413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747720","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-06","<p>18 financial penalties have been imposed to date on respondent employers for aggravated breaches of employment law under section 16 of the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013. Of these, 12 penalties have been paid and 6 remain unpaid either because the company has been dissolved or efforts by the debt collection agency for recovery of the amounts have been exhausted.</p><p>The total value of penalties imposed is just over £54,400. The total paid is just over £17,700, which was fully paid within 21 days so the 50% discount applied. The value of the 6 unpaid penalties is £19,000.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-06T16:19:03.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747720/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747720/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747720/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03","Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many financial penalties have been imposed to date on respondent employers for aggravated breach of employment law under section 16 of the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013; how many such penalties (a) have been paid and (b) remain unpaid; and what the total value is of penalties (i) imposed, (ii) paid and (iii) not yet paid.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","2414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747721","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-06","<p>Since April 2016, when the penalty regime for failure to pay employment tribunal awards started, 349 warning letters and 152 penalty notices have been issued.</p><p>Four financial penalties have been paid and 148 remain unpaid. Of these, 101 are being pursued through a debt collection agency, 20 were withdrawn because the employment tribunal award was paid, 10 are not enforceable due to liquidation and/or insolvency and 17 are within the payment period.</p><p>Over £500,000 in previously unpaid awards has been recovered following the issuing of only a warning letter. Over £91,000 has been recovered as a result of issuing both a warning letter and a penalty notice.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-06T16:17:17.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747721/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747721/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747721/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03","Employment Tribunals Service: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the Answer of 11 January 2017 to Question 58968, how many (a) warning letters and (b) financial penalty notices have been issued to respondent employers to date under section 150 of the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 for failure to pay an employment tribunal award; how many of those financial penalties (i) have been paid and (ii) remain unpaid; and how much in previously unpaid awards has been recovered by his Department following (A) the issuing of a warning letter only and (B) the issuing of both a warning letter and a financial penalty notice.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","2415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747722","Department of Health","false","2017-07-13","<p>The National Health Service and wider health system has examined how to sustain and improve care – which produced the NHS Five Year Forward View. The Government committed to providing an additional £10 billion in real terms by 2020-21 to back the NHS’s plan, enabling it to deliver key priorities like seven day care, improved access to cancer treatments and better mental health services.</p><p> </p><p>All public services, local NHS areas need to live within the budget agreed – otherwise they effectively take up resources that could be spent on general practitioners, mental health care, and cancer treatment. As part of their financial planning, NHS England and NHS Improvement have been running a process to look at how a small number of areas could do more to balance their financial plans, as many already have.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS is required to meet its operational standards as set out in the mandate and ensure access to appropriate care for all, in line with the NHS constitution. It is right that the NHS should consider efficiency savings such as reducing delayed transfers of care, reducing running costs, or reviewing treatments that are of low clinical effectiveness – because this improves patient care overall.</p><p>NHS England and NHS Improvement have designed and implemented the capped expenditure process working with the local NHS.</p><p> </p><p>Local communications are not held centrally.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","2488","2017-07-13T09:19:44.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747722/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747722/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-03","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will place in the Library a copy of (a) the document circulated to NHS officials in London on 25 May 2017 on the effect of the capped expenditure process, (b) any equivalent document circulated to such officials in other areas affected by the capped expenditure process and (c) the letter referred to in the 27 June 2017 edition of the Health Service Journal.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","2443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747723","Home Office","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Government’s review of funding for Islamist extremism in the UK was completed and reported to the Home Secretary and the Prime Minister in 2016. Ministers received advice on publication of the report from the Civil Service.</p><p> </p><p>Ministers have updated Parliament on the review today.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-12T12:32:48.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747723/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747723/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747723/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 3 July 2017 to Question 1467, when the report of the review into the funding of Islamist extremism was (a) finalised and (b) submitted to ministers; and from which external sources advice is being provided to ministers on publication of the report.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","2650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747724","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-06","<p>Each prison is required to have at least one family liaison officer or FLO. The FLO acts as the family’s chief point of contact with the prison. They must inform the prisoner’s nominated next of kin in person, as soon as possible following the prisoner’s death. If it is not possible to do this in person, for example because of distance, the FLO must arrange a follow-up visit promptly. They will then continue to meet the family and/or correspond with them, according to their wishes, to offer continuing information and support until all investigations of the death are concluded.</p><p> </p><p>Further details can be found in Prison Service Instruction 64/2011, which can be viewed on gov.uk.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-06T15:44:10.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747724/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747724/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-03","Prisoners: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how does a prison notify the next of kin of a prisoner's death in custody.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","2564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747725","Department of Health","false","2017-07-06","<p>Health services for people in prison are commissioned by NHS England.</p><p>Currently mental health services are delivered against a service specification which supports early assessment and management into treatment pathways.</p><p>People with low to medium level mental health needs can access short form talking therapies as part of services in the stepped care pathway model. Specialist and psychological services are commissioned to support people with more severe and enduring mental health need.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-06T09:54:43.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747725/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747725/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-03","Mental Health Services: Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what support is available for prisoners with mental health issues.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","2565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747726","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-06","<p>Improving safety is an urgent priority for this Government. We are taking immediate action to strengthen the frontline by recruiting around 2,500 more prison officers and rolling out improved training for staff on suicide and self-harm reduction.</p><p> </p><p>The Government publishes statistics on deaths in custody quarterly, and updated detailed tables annually. They can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2016--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2016--2</a>.</p><p>Numbers of deaths in custody for the last ten years (including those that were self-inflicted) are published in Table 1.1 of “Deaths in prison custody 1978 to 2016”. The tables will next be updated and published on 27 July 2017.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","2568","2017-07-06T15:40:38.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747726/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747726/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-03","Prisoners: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoner deaths attributed to suicide were recorded in prisons in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","2567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747727","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-06","<p>Improving safety is an urgent priority for this Government. We are taking immediate action to strengthen the frontline by recruiting around 2,500 more prison officers and rolling out improved training for staff on suicide and self-harm reduction.</p><p> </p><p>The Government publishes statistics on deaths in custody quarterly, and updated detailed tables annually. They can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2016--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2016--2</a>.</p><p>Numbers of deaths in custody for the last ten years (including those that were self-inflicted) are published in Table 1.1 of “Deaths in prison custody 1978 to 2016”. The tables will next be updated and published on 27 July 2017.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","2567","2017-07-06T15:40:38.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747727/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747727/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-03","Prisoners: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoner deaths were recorded in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","2568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747728","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-11","<p>As set out in the in the White Paper on Prison Safety and Reform in November 2016, we plan to set out a strategy for female offenders later this year. This will aim to improve outcomes for women in custody, and in the community.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-07-11T15:29:20.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747728/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747728/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747728/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-03","Offenders: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the White Paper on Prison safety and reform published in November 2016, when he plans to publish a strategy to improve the treatment of female offenders in custody and in the community.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","2500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747729","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-11","<p>The latest snapshot of the prison population as at 30 June, 2017, shows that there were 4,007 female prisoners, which is an increase of 36 from 2 June, 2017. From an analytical perspective, these increases are small, of less than 1%. It is too early to say what, if anything, is causing this increase.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-07-11T15:29:44.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747729/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747729/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747729/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-03","Prisoners: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the increase in the number of female prisoners in June 2017.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","2499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747730","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-11","<p>As set out in the November 2016 White Paper on Prison Safety and Reform, we plan to publish a strategy for female offenders later this year, and this will address how we can improve outcomes for women across the criminal justice system. The strategy will build on the existing work we are already funding in local areas to introduce a Whole Systems Approach, aimed at prevention and early intervention, and on our work to roll out Liaison and Diversion (L&amp;D) services across England. L&amp;D services, based at police stations and courts, help identify people with mental health issues, substance misuse problems and other vulnerabilities as soon as they come into contact with the criminal justice system, with a view to diverting them into treatment and support where appropriate.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-07-11T15:30:10.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747730/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747730/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747730/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-03","Prisoners: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to reduce the number of women in prison.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","2501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747731","Home Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government’s policy paper (Cm 9464), which was laid before Parliament on 26 June, sets out our proposals that European Union (EU) citizens who arrive in the UK before the specified date and have five years’ continuous residence in the UK will be able to apply for UK settled status.</p><p> </p><p>We will publish further detail on the specifics of the new application process for settled status, including specifying the length of the grace period, in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-10T13:01:01.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747731/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747731/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747731/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Government's publication entitled The United Kingdom's Exit from the European Union: Safeguarding the Position of EU Citizens Living in the UK and UK Nationals Living in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, when the length of the grace period referred to in paragraph 24 will be specified for EU nationals resident in the UK at the time the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","2449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747732","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-11","<p>Data relating to libraries is collected from local authorities by the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy which makes available the data annually to subscribers.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-07-11T15:23:42.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747732/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747732/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-03","Public Libraries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many local libraries have been operating in each region of England and Wales in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","2553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747733","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Government is taking strong action to deliver a long-term plan to eradicate bovine TB. The comprehensive strategy includes strengthening cattle testing and movement controls, improving biosecurity on farm and when trading, and badger control in areas where TB is rife.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The strategy is delivering results. Later this year we will apply for Officially TB free status in the Low Risk Area of the country where there is no significant TB in wildlife.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-07-12T11:07:24.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747733/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747733/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-03","Bovine Tuberculosis: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the 25 year strategy for tackling bovine TB.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","2579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747734","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-06","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-07-06T13:37:17.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747734/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747734/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-03","Air Pollution: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 29 June 2017 to Question 1033, what estimate his Department has made of the total cost to the public purse of court costs relating to air quality compliance cases in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","2611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747735","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-06","<p>We are listening to the agricultural sector, considering the latest data and working closely with industry to understand and analyse the labour demand and supply, now and when we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>For the longer-term, we are considering the options for our future immigration system carefully, and will look to develop a system which works for all. As part of this, the Government intends to commission advice from the Migration Advisory Committee to analyse the reliance on EU migrant workers across the economy and consider the UK’s labour market needs.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-07-06T10:19:23.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747735/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747735/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-03","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the future availability of seasonal labour in the agricultural sector.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","2541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747736","Department of Health","false","2017-07-06","<p>Most social workers are not employed by the National Health Service, however there are a small number who work within the social services care setting and are employed by the NHS.</p><p> </p><p>As of March 2017 NHS Digital data shows there are 327 full time equivalent social workers directly employed by the NHS in the West Midlands and seven full time equivalent social workers in Coventry.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-06T09:53:58.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747736/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747736/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-03","Social Workers: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many social workers are directly employed by the NHS in adult social care in (a) the West Midlands and (b) Coventry.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","2534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747737","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-06","<p>Market analysis relating to the potential for future naval exports is classified and commercially sensitive. There are therefore no plans to place such studies in the Library of the House.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-07-06T16:38:10.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747737/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747737/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-03","Exports: Defence Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will place in the Library studies produced by the Defence and Security Organisation and Defence Growth Partnership that examine the potential market landscape for UK naval exports in the five to 15-year market.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","2535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747738","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-11","<p>Work is on-going in the Ministry of Defence, led by Joint Forces Command, to determine the detailed requirements underpinning any future overland capability programme.</p><p>A number of space-based, manned and unmanned aircraft solutions, including the development of a sensor for integration onto P-8A, are being explored as part of this work.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","2551","2017-07-11T15:11:18.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747738/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747738/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747738/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-03","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department plans that the proposed RAF P-8A fleet take over overland surveillance roles currently performed by the Sentinel R1.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","2555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747739","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Ministry of Defence is critically reviewing all activities and functions undertaken by the civilian workforce. We will review and test, based on value for money assessments, how these activities and functions could best be done in the future. The achievement of the Department's objectives, including the delivery of front-line operational capabilities, remains our priority. Alternative delivery models will be evaluated.</p><p>The Department outsourced 4,090 staff between Financial Year (FY) 2012-13 and FY2016-17 (inclusive), broken down by year as follows: FY2012-13 (380 staff); FY2013-14 (zero staff); FY2014-15 (2,355 staff); FY2015-16 (1,130 staff) and FY2016-17 (225 staff).</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","2549 ; 2552","2017-07-11T16:15:39.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747739/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747739/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747739/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-03","Ministry of Defence: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department plans to outsource any of its jobs and functions to the private sector; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","2556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747740","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-06","<p>No decision has been taken on the future of Hyde Park Barracks.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-07-06T16:15:21.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747740/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747740/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747740/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-03","Hyde Park Barracks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans are in place to dispose of Hyde Park Barracks.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","2536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747741","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-06","<p>The Ministry of Defence is reviewing how it supports state ceremonial and Public Duties within London. So far no decisions have been made on the future of Hyde Park Barracks and, therefore, no decisions have been taken about future re-provision arrangements.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-07-06T16:15:49.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747741/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747741/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747741/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-03","Household Cavalry Mounted Regiment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his Department's plans are for the basing requirements for the Household Cavalry Mounted Regiment.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","2537"
