"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747057","Home Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government’s policy paper (Cm 9464), which was laid before Parliament on 26 June, sets out our proposals that European Union (EU) citizens who arrive in the UK before the specified date and have five years’ continuous residence in the UK will be able to apply for UK settled status.</p><p> </p><p>Work is underway to assess the proposed resources and costs required to implement the new settled status scheme.</p><p> </p><p>The details of the settled status scheme will be subject to negotiations and a reciprocal deal with the EU. We will publish further detail on the specifics of the new application process for settled status, including detailed eligibility criteria, in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","2271 ; 2274 ; 2275 ; 2277 ; 2308","2017-07-10T12:54:51.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747057/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747057/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-30","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Government's publication The United Kingdom's Exit from the European Union: Safeguarding the Position of EU Citizens Living in the UK and UK Nationals Living in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, what the effect is on an EU national's settled status of working for a UK employer outside the UK for more than two years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","2278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747058","Home Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government’s policy paper (Cm 9464), which was laid before Parliament on 26 June, sets out our proposals that European Union (EU) citizens who arrive in the UK before the specified date and have five years’ continuous residence in the UK will be able to apply for UK settled status.</p><p> </p><p>Work is underway to assess the proposed resources and costs required to implement the new settled status scheme.</p><p> </p><p>The details of the settled status scheme will be subject to negotiations and a reciprocal deal with the EU. We will publish further detail on the specifics of the new application process for settled status, including detailed eligibility criteria, in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","2274 ; 2275 ; 2277 ; 2278 ; 2308","2017-07-10T12:54:51.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747058/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747058/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-30","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Government's publication The United Kingdom's Exit from the European Union: Safeguarding the Position of EU Citizens Living in the UK and UK Nationals Living in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, whether EU nationals who refuse to provide biometric information will be eligible to apply for settled status in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","2271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747059","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-05","<p>I, and other Ministers, have regular conversations with other donors and Heads of agencies to discuss taking forwards reform of the international system and how we can all respond better to humanitarian crises. During the course of 2017 this has included specific conversations urging countries and institutions to step up their response to the major humanitarian crises, and pushing for a reformed system which is more efficient, innovative, transparent and accountable.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-05T16:40:58.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747059/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747059/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-06-30","UN Economic and Social Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her international counterparts on the World Humanitarian Summit in advance of UN Economic and Social Council meeting in June 2017; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","2282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747060","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-05","<p>The Mayor, Transport for London, the police and local authorities have a range of tools available to them to deal with congestion and parking issues as well as enforcement of the licensing regime. Effective use of these tools will allow both licensed taxi and PHVs to lawfully meet the demands of London’s travelling public.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-07-05T12:31:27.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747060/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747060/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-30","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to give Transport for London statutory power to cap the number of private hire vehicle licences it issues.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","2350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747061","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-07","<p>There have been no discussions between the Secretary of State and the Mayor of London on reforming the law to give Transport for London the power to cap the number of private hire vehicle driver licences. The Mayor has recently written to the Secretary of State for Transport requesting this reform as part of a wider package of measures. We will respond to him on this and the other matters raised in due course.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-07-07T08:40:24.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747061/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747061/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-30","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with the Mayor of London on the potential merits of reforming the law to give Transport for London the power to cap the number of private hire vehicle driver licences.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","2342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747062","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-05","<p>In its Answer of 18 April 2017 to Question 69488, the Government stated that it was conducting research on the effects of transparency in overseas money transfers (involving foreign exchange), on consumer decisions. This research will help to inform the Government's response to the consultation on draft regulations for the implementation of the Second Payment Services Directive. This response will be published shortly.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","2291","2017-07-05T16:02:41.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747062/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747062/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-30","Foreign Exchange","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 18 April 2017 to Question 69488, if he will publish the results of the research commissioned by his Department on the effect of pricing structures used by foreign exchange providers on consumer value choices.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","2292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747063","Home Office","false","2017-07-06","<p>The investigation and prosecution of individuals suspected of war crimes is an operational matter for the police. Any decision to investigate or prosecute is the responsibility of the police in consultation with Crown Prosecution Service. In particular, the War Crimes Team of the Metropolitan Police Counter Terrorism Command (SO15) has national responsibility within England and Wales for the investigation of such offences, including genocide, crimes against humanity and torture; it is their responsibility, accordingly, to determine the recourses necessary to carry out this function.</p><p> </p><p>Referrals from the public can be made directly to the War Crimes Team at the following email address:</p><p> </p><p>- <a href="mailto:SO15Mailbox.WarCrimesunit@met.pnn.police.uk" target="_blank">SO15Mailbox.WarCrimesunit@met.pnn.police.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidelines on this referral process can be found on the Crown Prosecution Service’s website:</p><p> </p><p>- <a href="https://www.cps.gov.uk/publications/agencies/war_crimes.html" target="_blank">https://www.cps.gov.uk/publications/agencies/war_crimes.html</a></p><p> </p><p>As policing is a devolved matter in Scotland and Northern Ireland, the responsibility for investigations into alleged war crime offences, and the referral system, is an operational matter for Police Scotland and the Police Service of Northern Ireland, respectively.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","2283","2017-07-06T12:01:18.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747063/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747063/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-30","War Crimes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what process is in place for individual constituents to bring alleged cases of war crimes to the attention of the war crimes unit and the relevant authorities.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","2281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747064","Home Office","false","2017-07-06","<p>The investigation and prosecution of individuals suspected of war crimes is an operational matter for the police. Any decision to investigate or prosecute is the responsibility of the police in consultation with Crown Prosecution Service. In particular, the War Crimes Team of the Metropolitan Police Counter Terrorism Command (SO15) has national responsibility within England and Wales for the investigation of such offences, including genocide, crimes against humanity and torture; it is their responsibility, accordingly, to determine the recourses necessary to carry out this function.</p><p> </p><p>Referrals from the public can be made directly to the War Crimes Team at the following email address:</p><p> </p><p>- <a href="mailto:SO15Mailbox.WarCrimesunit@met.pnn.police.uk" target="_blank">SO15Mailbox.WarCrimesunit@met.pnn.police.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidelines on this referral process can be found on the Crown Prosecution Service’s website:</p><p> </p><p>- <a href="https://www.cps.gov.uk/publications/agencies/war_crimes.html" target="_blank">https://www.cps.gov.uk/publications/agencies/war_crimes.html</a></p><p> </p><p>As policing is a devolved matter in Scotland and Northern Ireland, the responsibility for investigations into alleged war crime offences, and the referral system, is an operational matter for Police Scotland and the Police Service of Northern Ireland, respectively.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","2281","2017-07-06T12:01:18.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747064/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747064/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-30","War Crimes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what mechanisms are in place to enable people to bring allegations of war crimes to the attention of the appropriate authorities.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","2283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747065","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-05","<p>The Government undertook a technical review of the Standing Orders relating to English Votes for English Laws in October 2016. A report was subsequently published on 30 March 2017 in which the Government concluded that the procedures introduced by English Votes have shown to be working well and do not require substantive change at this time. However, Parliament and the Government will continue to work together in monitoring the operation of the procedures.</p><p> </p><p>A copy of the report can be found at the below address:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/english-votes-for-english-laws-review" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/english-votes-for-english-laws-review</a></p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-07-05T10:28:35.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747065/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747065/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-30","English Votes for English Laws","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he plans to review the operation of the English Votes for English Laws Standing Orders.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","2284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747066","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-07","<p>On 3 July the Secretary of State tabled a Written Ministerial Statement which advised Parliament that the UK had notified its intention to withdraw from the 1964 London Fisheries Convention.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-07-07T12:06:33.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747066/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747066/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-30","Fisheries Convention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether it is the Government's policy to leave the 1964 London Convention; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","2264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747067","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The civil service provided support for Government Ministers on issues relating to Government business. Beyond that this is a political agreement between two parties.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-07-10T14:24:39.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747067/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747067/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-30","Democratic Unionist Party","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what advice the Government received from sources outside the Civil Service on the agreement on confidence and supply recently reached between the Government and the Democratic Unionist Party.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","2263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747068","Department of Health","false","2017-07-05","<p>NHS Shared Business Services Ltd (SBS) is a joint venture company owned by the Department and Sopra Steria. It contracts with National Health Service trusts and foundation trusts and other NHS bodies to provide a range of services including finance and accounting services, procurement and human resources and payroll services. SBS wins contracts from NHS bodies by demonstrating value for money in its service offerings to them and we have no plans to review the payroll services carried out by the Company.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-05T16:16:01.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747068/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747068/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-30","NHS Shared Business Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will review NHS payroll service contracts held by Shared Business Services.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","2269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747069","Department of Health","false","2017-07-05","<p>The Government remains committed to reforming nursing, midwifery and allied health pre-registration education and increasing the number of places available for students so that two in three nursing applicants are no longer turned down for a place; at the same time ensuring these students have more cash available to them while they study. As a result, we expect these reforms to enable universities to create up to 10,000 additional nursing and other health professional training places by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>Health Education England is confident that the National Health Service will have the required number of students it needs starting courses this year and will continue to work with the education sector to deliver these reforms successfully for the longer term.</p><p> </p><p>It should also be noted that students will continue to apply for courses up to September and through clearing.</p><p> </p><p>Arrangements confirming the future clinical placement model will be published in due course.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-05T16:13:41.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747069/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747069/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-30","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of comments by the vice-chancellors of Worcester University and of West of England University that no new money has been made available to fund the promised 10,000 new training places for nurses after the abolition of nurse bursaries; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","2280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747070","Department for Education","false","2017-07-06","<p>Non-continuation rates for UK students at English Higher Education Institutions are lower than in 2009/10, including for the most disadvantaged students. Analysis by the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) has found that students’ age, subject studied and entry qualifications account for a substantial portion of the gap between the most and least disadvantaged students. The analysis is available here: <a href="http://www.hefce.ac.uk/analysis/ncr/nhe/" target="_blank">http://www.hefce.ac.uk/analysis/ncr/nhe/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>We want to continue to see reduced non-continuation rates for all students. The Higher Education and Research Act 2017 requires institutions to publish admissions and retention data by gender, ethnicity and socio-economic background, and this greater transparency will help the Higher Education sector make further progress to build on what has already been achieved. We are working closely with HEFCE and the Director of Fair Access to target resources effectively and to ensure that universities take more responsibility for widening access and retention for students from disadvantaged backgrounds, prioritising activities that demonstrate the greatest value for money.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-07-06T09:20:28.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747070/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747070/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-30","Students: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Office for Fair Access report, Outcomes of access agreement monitoring for 2015-16, published on 29 April 2017, what assessment her Department has made of the growing gap in non-continuation rates between the most disadvantaged and the most disadvantaged students after the first year at university.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","2316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747071","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-05","<p>The Chair and advisory panel members for the independent review of full-time social action by young people are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Chair</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Steve Holliday</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Panel</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Saeed Atcha</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Veronica Wadley</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Andy Haldane</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Professor Sue Maguire</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Charlotte Hill</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-05T16:36:28.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747071/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747071/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747071/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-30","Youth Social Action Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will publish the names of the members on the Youth Social Action Review advisory panel.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747072","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-05","<p>The Government is currently considering Lord Hodgson’s report on third party campaigning. It is considering the report alongside a number of other reports which have made recommendations about the framework of electoral law, such as the the Law Commission’s review of electoral law. The Government will respond to the issues raised in due course.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-07-05T16:10:26.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747072/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747072/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747072/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-30","Third Party Campaigning Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he plans to publish a response to the Third Party Campaigning Review.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747073","Home Office","false","2017-07-06","<p>The Government is clear that all use of force in prison and police custody – or any other setting – must be lawful, necessary, proportionate and conducted as safely as is possible. If officers need to use force, it is right that they are expected to account for their actions.</p><p>We are committed to improving transparency and accountability on the police use of force, which is why in 2014 the then Home Secretary asked former CC David Shaw (Chief Constable for West Mercia until July 2016) to lead a review into what data should be recorded and published. The review reported in 2015 and recommended the police record and publish the ethnicity, age, location and outcome for all incidents where a reasonable level of force is used, including physical restraint, less lethal weapons and firearms.</p><p>All police forces in England and Wales have been working to implement this data collection system from April 2017. All forces are expected to publish their record level use of force data for the first time this summer. A subset of this use of force data will also form part of the Home Office 2017-18 Annual Data Requirement, which will be published on GOV.UK in summer 2018.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-06T12:08:47.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747073/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747073/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747073/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-30","Restraint Techniques: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her Department's policy is on the disproportionate use of force against BME people in prison and police custody.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747074","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>We are committed to the Race Disparity Audit and expect to publish the findings soon.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-07-10T14:22:37.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747074/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747074/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-30","Public Sector: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he plans to publish the previous Government's audit on racial disparities in public services announced on 27 August 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747075","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-05","<p>The Department for Culture Media and Sport is working with the NCS Trust on a formal Treasury Minute Response to the Public Accounts Committee’s report. This Minute is currently scheduled for publication in the House of Commons in October 2017.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-05T09:39:51.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747075/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747075/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747075/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-30","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if the Government plans to respond to the Public Accounts Committee's report on the National Citizen Service, published on 6 March 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747076","Home Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>Collaboration is a key tool in helping the police become more responsive, more efficient and more effective at tackling crime. Police and Crime Commissioners and Chief Constables now have a statutory duty to consider and review collaboration agreements with other forces. The Government, through the police transformation fund, has also invested in collaborative projects as well as funding to champion a better understanding of crime in rural areas.</p><p>The election of Police and Crime Commissioners has given communities, including those in rural areas, a strong voice in determining how police resources are allocated to tackle the crimes that matter most to them.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-10T16:31:21.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747076/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747076/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747076/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-30","Crime: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to encourage cross-police force collaboration to tackle rural crime.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","2318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747077","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-07","<p>There are no published statistics on the annual number of passengers travelling on the East Coast Main Line.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics for the train operators serving the East Coast Main Line stations are available on the Office of Rail and Road data portal at the following link: <a href="http://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/browsereports/12" target="_blank">http://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/browsereports/12</a>.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-07T08:37:09.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747077/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747077/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747077/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-30","East Coast Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of trends in passenger numbers on the East Coast Main Line since 2010.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","2319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747078","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-10","<p>As highlighted in the new Transport Investment Strategy, the Department for Transport, where appropriate, will offer targeted support to local authorities to help develop their bidding and delivery capability thus ensuring all areas of the country have the potential to produce high quality business cases to realise the benefits that strong transport projects will unlock.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is also funding Local Authorities’ business case development costs for selected schemes within the Large Local Major schemes programme.</p><p> </p><p>In addition the Department has provided capacity support to Local Enterprise Partnerships and Local Authorities through the Transport Delivery Excellence Programme in collaboration with the Local Enterprise Partnership Network.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-10T14:03:51.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747078/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747078/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747078/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-30","Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he has taken to increase the capacity of local authorities to produce business cases for major transport projects.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","2320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747079","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-10","<p>Assessment of the New Stations Fund bids is now complete and I hope to announce the successful projects shortly.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-10T13:56:52.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747079/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747079/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747079/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-30","Railway Stations: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to announce the next round of the New Stations Fund scheme; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","2315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747080","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-05","<p>The government remains committed to the Social Value Act and continues to implement the recommendations of the Lord Young Review. We will make an announcement on the Public Services (Social Value) Act in due course.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-05T16:32:34.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747080/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747080/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747080/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-30","Public Services (Social Value) Act 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, when she plans to publish the Government's 2017 review of the Social Value Act.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","2337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747081","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The British Indian Ocean Territory's Employment Ordinance No.7 of 1984 covers various aspects of employment on BIOT and is available in the House of business library.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-10T15:47:25.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747081/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747081/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747081/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-30","British Indian Ocean Territory: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what employment laws are currently in force in the British Indian Ocean Territory.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","2297"
