"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746722","Women and Equalities","false","2017-07-05","<p>We committed to a review of the Gender Recognition Act as part of our response to the Women and Equalities Select Committee report on transgender equality. Through this review we are examining options to streamline and demedicalise the gender recognition process.</p><p>The review is ongoing and we will provide an update on the Government’s progress as soon as possible.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-05T15:36:57.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746722/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746722/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-06-29","Gender Recognition Act 2004","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what progress has been made on the review of the Gender Recognition Act 2004.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","2043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746723","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-06","<p>The Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union has not met with the Secretariat of the European Free Trade Association. He met with the President of the EFTA Court in October 2016.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-06T15:12:14.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746723/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746723/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746723/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-06-29","European Free Trade Association","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what recent meetings he has had with the secretariat of the European Free Trade Association.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","2044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746724","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-06","<p>With the support of the Department of Health, the Campaign to End Loneliness developed a toolkit for Health and Wellbeing Boards to help them better understand, identify and commission interventions for the issue of loneliness in older age. This was published in 2013 and can be found here: <a href="http://campaigntoendloneliness.org/guidance/" target="_blank">http://campaigntoendloneliness.org/guidance/</a></p><p>In 2013-14, the Department of Health also added a measure of loneliness to the Adult Social Care Outcomes Framework and to the updated Public Health Outcomes Framework. Local authorities can use this as guidance in identifying local needs.</p><p>There are various statutory requirements on local authorities to develop strategic planning documents. Local authorities are encouraged to make use of the best available data in developing these documents. Local authorities must also have regard to their public sector equality duty, which requires public bodies to have due regard to the need to eliminate discrimination, advance equality of opportunity and foster good relations between different people when carrying out their activities.</p><p>The Housing White Paper set out two ways in which the planning system will be used to deliver more suitable homes for older and disabled people:</p><ul><li><p>Paragraph 1.16 confirmed the strengthening of the National Planning Policy Framework so that local planning authorities are expected to have clear policies for addressing the housing requirements of groups with particular needs, such as elderly and disabled people; and,</p></li><li><p>The Neighbourhood Planning Bill introduced a new statutory duty on the Secretary of State to produce guidance for local planning authorities on how their local development documents should meet the housing needs of older and disabled people. Guidance produced will place clearer expectations about planning to meet the needs of older people, including supporting the development of such homes near local services.</p></li></ul>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","1955","2017-07-06T15:53:13.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746724/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746724/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-29","Loneliness: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will provide guidance to local authorities on using Age UK's loneliness heat map to identify local needs.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","1954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746725","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-06","<p>With the support of the Department of Health, the Campaign to End Loneliness developed a toolkit for Health and Wellbeing Boards to help them better understand, identify and commission interventions for the issue of loneliness in older age. This was published in 2013 and can be found here: <a href="http://campaigntoendloneliness.org/guidance/" target="_blank">http://campaigntoendloneliness.org/guidance/</a></p><p>In 2013-14, the Department of Health also added a measure of loneliness to the Adult Social Care Outcomes Framework and to the updated Public Health Outcomes Framework. Local authorities can use this as guidance in identifying local needs.</p><p>There are various statutory requirements on local authorities to develop strategic planning documents. Local authorities are encouraged to make use of the best available data in developing these documents. Local authorities must also have regard to their public sector equality duty, which requires public bodies to have due regard to the need to eliminate discrimination, advance equality of opportunity and foster good relations between different people when carrying out their activities.</p><p>The Housing White Paper set out two ways in which the planning system will be used to deliver more suitable homes for older and disabled people:</p><ul><li><p>Paragraph 1.16 confirmed the strengthening of the National Planning Policy Framework so that local planning authorities are expected to have clear policies for addressing the housing requirements of groups with particular needs, such as elderly and disabled people; and,</p></li><li><p>The Neighbourhood Planning Bill introduced a new statutory duty on the Secretary of State to produce guidance for local planning authorities on how their local development documents should meet the housing needs of older and disabled people. Guidance produced will place cle